Subject:    MX and crock records.
From:       <a href="?a=95837786200001&r=1&w=2">"Rich DeJordy, x295" &lt;RAD () MATH ! AMS ! COM&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198904">1989-04-14 14:04:02</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626865&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626865&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Hello,


     I am trying to understand the domain name service that we offer to the
     net to resolve our Class B address.  There are two questions I have
     now, and they are totally uninformed and (hopefully) simple.

     1)  Both of our name servers are local, and when our gateway decides
     to be tempermental, we are not resolving anything.  So, another site
     has offered to provide backup DNS service.  In doing so, they wanted
     me to change the refresh and retry intervals, the expiration limit,
     and the Min RR TTL binding.  I can look up the effects of these
     myself, but do I need to add NS records to my domain tables for the
     other hosts?  All intuition tells me I should, but...

     2)  In the zone files from before I got here, there was an entry for
     *.AMS.COM to point to a specific node.  When I point this at my
     VAXcluster, and users enter information wrong, (e.g. forget to append
     .bitnet) it becomes @host.AMS.COM and then the VAX refuses to talk to
     itself and I get failed messages.  I removed this record from the
     domain name service, but am wondering if there's a way to resolve
     *.AMS.COM to MATH.AMS.COM for non-local requests and still have them
     be wrong for internal resolution?  (Is this part of my domain software
     or of my mailer?)  (Why would I want to do/not do this for external
     sites?) 

     Thanks for any information this may provide.
-------

